		<td><b>Q on testing vblank efficiency</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Alrighty, I've not seen any bugs and I'm pretty sure my routines are all optimized (or good enough anyway...)
<br />
<br />I just want to know if there's a way to test on a frame-by-frame basis how much vblank/CPU was used to get an idea of how well I coded something.  
<br />
<br />I've heard of something like breakpoints with FCE XDSP (whatever it's called), but have no idea how to actually do those.
<br />
<br />So, what can I do and is there anything I should be looking for?
<br />
<br />I hope the post makes sense.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>MottZilla</b> [ Mon Sep 08, 2008 2:05 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In Nintendulator, you can put a break point on the NMI address. Then put a break point on the RTI from your NMI. Then you could see what cycle and scanline NMI starts and when it finishes up. This would let you see how much time you used and what was left.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
